introduction.p:
Recall that for \uvec{u} = (u_1,u_2,\dotsc,u_n) and \uvec{v} = (v_1,v_2,\dotsc,v_n), the dot product of \uvec{u} and \uvec{v} is defined by the formula given below on the left. It is an important formula because if \theta is the angle between two nonzero vectors \uvec{u} and \uvec{v}, then \theta satisfies both 0 \le \theta \le \pi and the formula given below on the right.

	\udotprod{u}{v} \amp= u_1 v_1 + u_2 v_2 + \dotsb + u_n v_n \amp
	\cos\theta \amp= \frac{\udotprod{u}{v}}{\unorm{u}\unorm{v}}
